}
```

This will return the wrong child if a different display object is added at index 0.

This allows a pause between repeats. Two typical use cases:

1) simply pause between each repetition of the tween

2) perform the first section of a tween, pause, then reverse the tween

Example of use case 2:

<pre>
tween.repeatDelay = PAUSE_TIME;
tween.repeatCount = 2;
tween.reverse = true;
</pre>


This is done by simply subtracting the delay time from mCurrentTime when the tween is repeating.

Posting this for another user who reported this problem. I just ran across it myself.

http://forum.starling-framework.org/topic/tween-reset-problem?replies=4

When onComplete is used to reset and start a Tween again, the Tween is never started.

In the latest code, REMOVE_FROM_JUGGLER is fired after the onComplete event, removing it from the juggler right after the onComplete adds it again.

<pre lang="as3">
if (previousTime < mTotalTime && mCurrentTime >= mTotalTime)
{
    if (mRepeatCount == 0 || mRepeatCount > 1)
    {
        mCurrentTime = 0.0;
        mCurrentCycle++;
        if (mRepeatCount > 1) mRepeatCount--;
    }
    else
    {
        if (mOnComplete != null) mOnComplete.apply(null, mOnCompleteArgs);
        dispatchEventWith(Event.REMOVE_FROM_JUGGLER);
    }
}
</pre>


A workaround would be to use a setTimeout or similar to put in back in a millisecond later.

In the previous version, this code was reversed:

<pre lang="as3">
if (previousTime < mTotalTime && mCurrentTime >= mTotalTime)
{
    dispatchEventWith(Event.REMOVE_FROM_JUGGLER);
    if (mOnComplete != null) mOnComplete.apply(null, mOnCompleteArgs);
}
</pre>


So it looks like the problem was introduced with the repeat code.
